<F P=100> LIFE SCIENCES </F>
<F P=101> MEDICINE AND PUBLIC HEALTH </F>
<H3> <TI>   Results of Medical Genetic Research on and the Frequency </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Results of Medical Genetic Research on and the Frequency </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
of   Different Types of Chromosome Aberrations in the Population 
of the Region Adjacent to the Semipalatinsk Nuclear Test Range 

<F P=102> 947C0173D Almaty ZDRAVOOKHRANENIYE KAZAKHSTANA in Russian 
No. 6, Jun 93 pp 14-16--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 947C0173D </F>
<F P=104>  Almaty ZDRAVOOKHRANENIYE KAZAKHSTANA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by N. Zh. Chayzhunusova, Kazakh Scientific Research </F>
Institute of Radiation Medicine and Ecology, Semipalatinsk; UDC 
616-092:612.014.481//482] 
  [Text] Abstract: A study was conducted of the 
frequency of congenital developmental defects and monogenic 
genetic diseases in children residing in Beskaragayskiy, 
Zhanasemeyskiy and Abayskiy rayons, Semipalatinsk Oblast 
adjacent to the nuclear test range. It was established that the 
frequency of occurrence of congenital developmental defects in 
children was elevated in these regions. 
  Four bibliographic reference, two tables. 
  Key Words: congenital developmental defects, chromosome 
aberration, nuclear radiation. 
  The mutagenic effects of ionizing radiation have been 
illuminated rather extensively in the literature [2,4,6,8]. 
Their registration is one of the approaches to biological 
dosimetry [3,5,9,10]. At the same time the structure and 
occurrence of genetic pathology in the population of a region 
within which nuclear explosions were actually carried out over 
the course of four decades have not been addressed by 
researchers. Nor has there been any research on the frequency of 
detection of different types of chromosome aberrations in 
lymphocytes of the blood of persons living in direct proximity 
to a test range. The purpose of this paper is to fill in this 
blank. The need for it was brought about by the absence of 
dependable information on the dose loads experienced by people 
who suffered from nuclear weapon tests. These dose loads may be 
estimated indirectly using the results of research on the 
frequency of detection of chromosome aberrations in different 
age groups. 
<H5>  Materials and Methods </H5>
  We analyzed statistical reporting materials of public health 
agencies, the birth and developmental histories of newborn 
infants, and records of autopsies of children who died at an age 
of up to 1 year in Semipalatinsk. We took account of cases of 
congenital developmental defects and diagnosis of hereditary 
diseases. We studied the frequency of detection of congenital 
developmental defects and monogenic genetically caused diseases 
in Beskaragayskiy, Zhanasemeyskiy and Abayskiy rayons, which 
suffered the most from the effects of ionizing radiation, and 
Kokpektinskiy Rayon as a control. Cytogenetic research was 
conducted on material from 31 clinically healthy students of the 
Semipalatinsk Medical Institute, 11 of whom (21.4 years old on 
the average) lived outside the northeastern region of Kazakhstan 
prior to entering the VUZ and who had resided for not more than 
2 years in Semipalatinsk before the time of their examination. 
They made up the first group of subjects. The second included 11 
students (20.8 years old on the average) who were indigenous 
inhabitants of Semipalatinsk. A third group was made up of nine 
students in their first and second years, who lived in Mayskiy 
Rayon, Pavlodar Oblast, which is directly adjacent to the test 
area, prior to entering the institute. 
  The frequency of chromosome aberrations was determined by 
cytological analysis of preparations of metaphasic chromosomes 
obtained by culturing lymphocytes from peripheral blood by the 
micromethod [7]. One hundred metaphase plates, selected 
according to criteria recommended in [1], were analyzed for each 
individual. A total of 3,100 metaphase plates were studied. 
<H5>  Research Results and Discussion </H5>
  Data on the occurrence and structure of genetic pathology in 
the child population of different rayons adjacent to the test 
range are presented in Table 1. 



  Table 1. Occurrence and Structure of Genetic Pathology in the Child Population of Rayons 
Adjacent to the Semipalatinsk Nuclear Test Range. 



Form of          Frequency of Detection of Genetic Abnormalities 
Pathology 
Revealed 

                 Beskaragayskiy      Zhanasemeyskiy      Abayskiy Rayon      Kokpektinskiy 
                 Rayon               Rayon                                   Rayon 

Congenital       0.73 +/- 0.007,     0.47 +/- 0.006,     0.29 +/- 0.006,     0.22 +/- 0.005 
developmental    P[.sub]1[/]&lt;0.001    P[.sub]2[/]&lt;0.001    P[.sub]3[/]&lt;0.001 
defects 

Monogenic                            0.02 +/- 0.002      0.29 +/-0.006       0.07 +/- 0.003 
diseases 

Total                                0.49 +/- 0.006      0.58 +/- 0.007      0.29 +/- 0.066 


Note: P[.sub]1[/]--significance of differences between indicators of Beskaragayskiy and 
Kokpektinskiy rayons; P[.sub]2[/] --significance of differences between indicators of 
Zhanasemeyskiy and Kokpektinskiy rayons; P[.sub]3[/]--significance of differences between 
indicators of Abayskiy and Kokpektinskiy rayons. 


  As we can see, the frequency of detection of congenital 
developmental defects was highest in Beskaragayskiy Rayon--1.5 
+/-0.004 percent--that is 10.47 per 1,000 population. This 
indicator was 3.3 times higher than that for children residing 
in Kokpektinskiy Rayon (control), it was 1.6 times higher than 
that found in Zhanasemeyskiy, and 2.6 times higher than the 
indicator in Abayskiy Rayon. These differences were 
statistically highly significant (P[.sub]1[/]&lt;0.001, 
P[.sub]2[/]&lt;0.001, P[.sub]3[/]&lt;0.001). 
  One of the most important causes of the appearance of 
congenital developmental defects in children is chromosome 
abnormalities, the frequency of which typically rises in 
response to ionizing radiation [4,5,6]. The results of research 
on the frequency of different types of aberrations in 
chromosomes in the lymphocytes of the blood of persons residing 
in the region adjacent to the test range are shown in Table 2. 



  Table 2. Frequency of Different Types of Aberrations of Chromosomes in 
Lymphocytes of the Blood of Persons Residing in a Region Adjacent to the 
Semipalatinsk Nuclear Test Range 



Group of    n             Aberrant    Total Number   Chromosome     Chromatid 
Subjects                  cells, /%   of             Type           Type 
                                      Aberrations    Aberrations    Aberrations 
                                      per 100 
                                      Cells 

First       11            1.9 +/-     2.0 +/- 0.24   0.94 +/-0.31   1.06 +/- 
group                     0.23                                      0.33 

Second      11            3.2 +/-     3.2 +/- 1.2    2.41 +/-0.69   0.79 +/- 
group                     1.2                                       0.29 

Third       9             3.7 +/-     3.8 +/- 0.35   1.9 +/-0.36    1.9 +/- 0.29 
group                     0.3 

            P[.sub]1[/]    &lt;0.001      &lt;0.001         &lt;0.05          &lt;0.05 

            P[.sub]2[/]    &gt; 0.1        &gt; 0.1           &gt; 0.1           &lt;0.05 

            P[.sub]3[/]    &gt; 0.1        &gt; 0.1           &gt; 0.1           &gt; 0.1 

Note: P[.sub]1[/]--significance of differences between indicators for subjects in 
the first and third groups; P[.sub]2[/] --significance of differences between 
indicators for subjects in the second and third groups; P[.sub]3[/]--significance 
of differences between indicators for subjects in the first and second groups. 


  As we can see, the frequency of detection of aberrant cells 
was 1.9 +/- 0.3 percent for students from outside the city prior 
to entering the medical institute (first group), it was 3.2 +/- 
1.2 percent for students who were indigenous inhabitants of 
Semipalatinsk (second group), which was 1.5 times higher than 
for the first group, although this difference was not 
statistically significant (P&gt; 0.1). This indicator was 3.7 +/- 
0.3 percent for students who had resided in Mayskiy Rayon, 
Pavlodar Oblast prior to entering the VUZ (third group), which 
was 1.95 times higher than for subjects of the first group. This 
difference was statistically highly significant (P&lt;0.001). A 
tendency for the frequency of detection of aberrant cells in 
students of the third group to rise in comparison with the 
second was also detected, although this difference was not 
statistically significant (P&gt; 0.1). 
  The total number of chromosome aberrations in students of 
the 
first group was 2.0 +/- 0.24 per 100 cells--that is 1.6 times 
lower than in the second group (3.2 +/- 1.2 per 100 cells). This 
difference was not statistically significant (P&gt; 0.1). However, 
the number of chromosome aberrations in students of the second 
group was found to be 1.9 times higher than for students of the 
first, with the statistical significance of the indicated 
differences being high (P&lt;0.001). 
  When we studied the types of aberrations we found that the 
chromosome type was encountered significantly more often in 
persons of the third group than in persons of the first 
(P&lt;0.05). Chromatid aberrations were encountered significantly 
more often in persons of the third group than in the second 
(P&lt;0.5) and first (P&lt;0.05) groups. 
  We know that the frequency of spontaneous aberrations of 
chromosomes in lymphocytes in human peripheral blood, determined 
in special research using large samples, is sufficiently low, 
varying on the average from 1.0 to 1.2 percent [1]. In this case 
it does not depend on the sex of the subjects, but it increases 
with age, attaining 5-6 percent in persons over 60 years old. In 
this connection we selected groups that were homogeneous with 
respect to age for our research. 
  Thus our research established that the frequency of 
chromosome aberrations in students who were inhabitants of 
Mayskiy Rayon, which is directly adjacent to the Semipalatinsk 
nuclear test range, was the highest. Moreover we also discovered 
a tendency for the frequency of detection of chromosome 
aberrations in students who were indigenous inhabitants of 
Semipalatinsk to increase in comparison with students who lived 
outside the northeastern region of Kazakhstan prior to entering 
the medical institute. 
  It is evident from Table 1 that the frequency of detection 
of 
monogenic genetically caused diseases was highest in 
Beskaragayskiy Rayon (0.31 +/- 0.007 percent), while in 
Zhanasemeyskiy Rayon it was 3.5 times lower that the indicator 
for Kokpektinskiy Rayon, the population of which suffered to a 
relatively lesser degree from ionizing radiation as a result of 
the test range's operation. This can apparently be explained by 
the fact that point mutations play the dominant role in the 
advent of monogenic diseases, and according to some data [6,8] 
their frequency changes insignificantly in response to small 
doses of ionizing radiation. 
  Thus our research established a rise in frequency of 
occurrence of congenital developmental defects in the child 
population residing in the vicinity of the Semipalatinsk nuclear 
test range. This pattern is explained by the higher frequency of 
chromosome aberrations detected in persons residing permanently 
in the region; a tendency for this frequency to rise with 
decreasing distance from the test range was also observed. The 
influence of its factors on the frequency of occurrence of 
monogenic genetically caused diseases could not be established 
dependably in this research; this question does need additional 
study. 
Bibliography 
