<H3> <TI>   Suppression of Speckle Noise in Radar Images </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Suppression of Speckle Noise in Radar Images </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   947G0013C Novosibirsk AVTOMETRIYA in Russian No. 5, Sep 
93-Oct 93 (manuscript received 24 may 89) pp 96-102 </F>

<F P=103> 947G0013C </F>
<F P=104>  Novosibirsk AVTOMETRIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by N. V. Rodionova, V. P. Sinilo, Fryazino, Moscow </F>
Oblast; UDC 62 1.396.96:621.391.26] 
  [Abstract] This article examines three possible approaches 
to the suppression of speckle noise in radar images: incoherent 
integration, nonlinear image filtering, and homomorphic 
processing. Merely increasing the number of uncorrelated 
measurements, the first method, is a radical method. At least 
four-to five-fold incoherent integration is necessary for 
satisfactory perception of a radar image. The other two methods 
may be used successfully only for certain types of radar ima ge 
processing. Three types of smoothing by filtering are examined. 
The filtering methods are intended to suppress the large 
scatters characteristic of high resolution radar image speckle 
noise. A table contrasts the results obtained using various 
filtering methods on an image of the surface of Venus. Nonlinear 
filtering reduces the level of speckle noise, and image 
distortions have a noise-like character. Homomorphic processisng 
also reduces the level of speckle noise, but the image is 
distorted by smoothing. Figures 7; table 1; references 5: 1 
Russian, 4 Western. 

</TEXT>

